<span id="freeTextContainer8886529161822335487">DNF @ 34%<br/><br/>This is reading like a history book. <b>A really boring history book.</b> But somehow the author also manages to make references to things/people during this time period as if the reader already knew all about it, which I absolutely did not and thus had to Wikipedia things. Then the parts that do not focus on the Irish War of Independence instead focused on exciting things such as - going shopping for clothing and toiletries. I just can&apos;t force myself to read this anymore. So disappointing con</span>
  <span id="freeText8886529161822335487" style="display:none">DNF @ 34%<br /><br />This is reading like a history book. <b>A really boring history book.</b> But somehow the author also manages to make references to things/people during this time period as if the reader already knew all about it, which I absolutely did not and thus had to Wikipedia things. Then the parts that do not focus on the Irish War of Independence instead focused on exciting things such as - going shopping for clothing and toiletries. I just can't force myself to read this anymore. So disappointing considering how much I really enjoyed <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/29638166.From_Sand_and_Ash" title="From Sand and Ash by Amy Harmon" rel="nofollow noopener">From Sand and Ash</a> and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/29008738.The_Bird_and_the_Sword__The_Bird_and_the_Sword_Chronicles___1_" title="The Bird and the Sword (The Bird and the Sword Chronicles, #1) by Amy Harmon" rel="nofollow noopener">The Bird and the Sword</a>.</span>
